defaulthe Deputy Mayor 
defaultalso 
defaultsought to limit the 
defaultrole of the 
defaultAssembly’s Police and Crime 
defaultCommittee and the information available to it. The Committee argued that effectively holding MOPAC to account requires the Committee to look in detail at the full range of areas of policing and crime reduction, whether or not a particular area i
defaults a current priority for MOPAC. 
defaultPolice and crime panels need to understand the broad policing landscape in their area and must have the ability to investigate issues that are not priorities for their elected commissioners. 
defaultBecause the legislation does not set out in detail what information and access police and crime panels should have, this can depend on the individuals in elected commissioner posts. In our case, it took the intervention of the Mayor to resolve some of the issues we faced following a new Deputy Mayor’s appointment. This must lead to a concern that
default, without clearer guidance,
default 
defaultn
defaultew individual
defaults
default 
defaultin the elected commissioner posts might bring a new set of challenges 
defaultfor police and crime panels 
default– e.g. different expectations around transparency
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are, however, areas where a lack of information has made our scrutiny work more difficult. Decisions previously taken in public by the Metropolitan Police Authority (MPA), supported by public reports and minutes, are now often made in private between the Deputy Mayor and the Met. Our recent investigation of the decision to expand Taser deployment in London demonstrated why such discussions must take place in public. Despite assurances that MOPAC would provide more public information than the MPA, less information is now available than under the old regime. The periodic updates received by the MPA on a range of programmes and strategies being pursued by the Met are no longer available and monthly financial information, previously reported through the MPA Finance and Resources Committee, was entirely withdrawn for a time and now published in a more limited way. 
default&#xa0;
defaultSince it was established
default,
default the 
defaultAssembly’s Police and Crime 
defaultCommittee 
defaulthas
default 
defaultinvestigated issues that are important for Londoners and held the Deputy Mayor to account on a cross-party basis. 
defaultAs 
defaultexample
defaults,
default t
defaulthe Committee has made 
defaultre
defaultcommendations 
defaultto improve MOPAC’s proposals for new Safer Neighbourhood Boards;
